Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["STFactor", "ObjectName",ExpressionUUID->"2ac3cd6f-5f38-498c-9a06-601afefc2232"],

Cell[BoxData[GridBox[{
   {Cell[TextData[{
     StyleBox["STFactor", "TI"],
     " \[LineSeparator], x_i \[RightArrow] x_i/\[Lambda] for each component \
\\rho_i > 0) and then apply STFactor to the result."
    }], "TableText",ExpressionUUID->"1870fe9d-0ac5-4f93-9eb7-f6bd98b716a7"]}
  },
  GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}},
  GridBoxItemSize->{
   "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}]], "Usage",
 CellID->1,ExpressionUUID->"efe2cd37-d116-4d0a-84db-40559c5e2908"],

Cell["\<\
STFactor factorizes products inside powers that depend on \[CurlyEpsilon]: it \
splits (a\[CenterDot] b)^{c\[CurlyEpsilon]+d} into a^{c\[CurlyEpsilon]+d}\\, \
b^{c\[CurlyEpsilon]+d} whenever one of the factors is manifestly positive for \
positive integration variables: (see example below) A typical usage is to \
rescale the integration variables along a ray \\rho of the Newton polytope \
(e.g., x_i \[RightArrow] x_i/\[Lambda] for each component \\rho_i > 0) and \
then apply STFactor to the result. The factorized form makes the \
\[Lambda]-dependence explicit, revealing whether the integrand diverges or \
converges along that ray.\
\>", "Notes",ExpressionUUID->"02271b87-368d-4805-bdec-a3db90ea1e0a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"STFactor", "[", "expression", "]"}]], "Input",ExpressionUUID->"9beaf79f-06a6-4697-a907-618c215383c9"]
}, Open  ]],

